## Fix: Collect and re-throw errors after all handlers have been called

The standard approach is to let every handler run, then surface any errors that occurred. If there's exactly one error, re-throw it directly. If there are multiple, wrap them in an `AggregateError`.

```typescript
emit(event: string, data?: unknown): void {
  const handlers = this.subs.get(event)
  if (!handlers) return

  const errors: unknown[] = []

  for (const handler of handlers.values()) {
    try {
      handler(data)
    } catch (err) {
      errors.push(err)
    }
  }

  if (errors.length === 1) throw errors[0]
  if (errors.length > 1) throw new AggregateError(errors, `${errors.length} handler(s) threw during emit("${event}")`)
}
```

### Why this approach

| Concern | Decision |
|---|---|
| All subscribers must run | Errors are caught per-handler and deferred |
| Errors must not be silently swallowed | They are re-thrown after the loop |
| Single error | Re-thrown as-is to preserve the original type/stack |
| Multiple errors | Wrapped in `AggregateError` (built-in since ES2021, Node 15+) so no information is lost |

